response:
 There are five choices for the first person, four for the second, and so on. So there are, in all,  \emph{5}\textasciimath\textperiodcentered  \textasciitilde4\textasciimath\textperiodcentered  \textasciitilde3\textasciimath\textperiodcentered  \textasciitilde2\textasciimath\textperiodcentered  \textasciitilde1 ways to seat five people on five chairs. However, not everyone will fit in that row of five chairs. Three of the possible seating arrangements will have two people sitting together and the other three will have three people sitting together. We have to subtract the number of these undesirable ways to obtain the number of acceptable ways.
</think> <answer> \begin{align*} &\text{Total number of ways without restriction}\\ &= 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 \quad\quad\big(\text{This is 5!}\big)\\ &= 120\\  &\text{Subtract the number of ways that are not acceptable:}\\ &\qquad\text{Two people sit together: }\binom{4}{2} \cdot2!\cdot3!\\ &\qquad\text{Three people sit together: }\binom{4}{3} \cdot3!\cdot2!\\ &= 48 + 48\\ &= 96\\ \therefore&\text{The number of acceptable ways}=120-96=24 \end{align*}
</answer>

